[ASSISTANT] To add space between rows in a `RecyclerView` with a `GridLayoutManager` in Kotlin, you can use `ItemDecoration`. This allows you to customize the spacing between items.

Here's an example code to achieve this:

```kotlin
import android.graphics.Rect
import android.view.View
import androidx.recyclerview.widget.GridLayoutManager
import androidx.recyclerview.widget.RecyclerView

class GridSpacingItemDecoration(private val spanCount: Int, private val spacing: Int, private val includeEdge: Boolean) : RecyclerView.ItemDecoration() {

    override fun getItemOffsets(outRect: Rect, view: View, parent: RecyclerView, state: RecyclerView.State) {
        val position = parent.getChildAdapterPosition(view) // item position
        val column = position % spanCount // item column

        if (includeEdge) {
            outRect.left = spacing - column * spacing / spanCount
            outRect.right = (column + 1) * spacing / spanCount

            if (position < spanCount) { // top edge
                outRect.top = spacing
            }
            outRect.bottom = spacing // item bottom
        } else {
            outRect.left = column * spacing / spanCount
            outRect.right = spacing - (column + 1) * spacing / spanCount
            if (position >= spanCount) {
                outRect.top = spacing // item top
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Here's how you can use it in your `RecyclerView` setup:

```kotlin
val spanCount = 2 // or however many columns you want
val spacing = 16 // the spacing in pixels

val layoutManager = GridLayoutManager(this, spanCount)
recyclerView.layoutManager = layoutManager

// Add spacing between items
recyclerView.addItemDecoration(GridSpacingItemDecoration(spanCount, spacing, true))

// Create and set your adapter
val adapter = YourAdapter(data)
recyclerView.adapter = adapter
```

In this code, the `GridSpacingItemDecoration` class calculates the spacing between items based on the span count and desired spacing. It then applies this spacing to the `RecyclerView`. Adjust the `spanCount` and `spacing` variables according to your requirements.

[ASSISTANT] To get the width of a view in Kotlin, you can use the `width` property. However, you need to make sure that you're accessing it after the view has been measured and laid out. 

Here's an example of how you can do it:

```kotlin
val view = findViewById<View>(R.id.your_view_id) // Replace with your view's ID

view.viewTreeObserver.addOnPreDrawListener(object : ViewTreeObserver.OnPreDrawListener {
    override fun onPreDraw(): Boolean {
        val width = view.width // This will give you the width of the view in pixels
        // Do something with the width

        // It's important to remove the listener once you're done with it to avoid memory leaks
        view.viewTreeObserver.removeOnPreDrawListener(this)
        return true
    }
})
```

In this example, replace `R.id.your_view_id` with the ID of the view you want to get the width of. This code sets up a `OnPreDrawListener` which will be called before the view is drawn on the screen. This is a good time to get the width of the view.

Remember to remove the listener once you have obtained the width to prevent any potential memory leaks.

