[ASSISTANT] To restrict a `ScrollView` from scrolling programmatically in Android, you can use a custom `ScrollView` class and override the `onTouchEvent` method to consume touch events without passing them to the superclass. Here's an example:

```java
import android.content.Context;
import android.util.AttributeSet;
import android.view.MotionEvent;
import android.widget.ScrollView;

public class NonScrollableScrollView extends ScrollView {

    public NonScrollableScrollView(Context context) {
        super(context);
    }

    public NonScrollableScrollView(Context context, AttributeSet attrs) {
        super(context, attrs);
    }

    public NonScrollableScrollView(Context context, AttributeSet attrs, int defStyle) {
        super(context, attrs, defStyle);
    }

    @Override
    public boolean onTouchEvent(MotionEvent ev) {
        // Consume touch events without passing them to the superclass
        return false;
    }
}
```

To use this custom `ScrollView`, you would need to replace instances of `<ScrollView>` in your layout XML files with `<your.package.name.NonScrollableScrollView>`. Make sure to replace `your.package.name` with the actual package name of your application.

For example, if your package name is `com.example.myapp`, you would use:

```xml
<com.example.myapp.NonScrollableScrollView
    android:layout_width="match_parent"
    android:layout_height="match_parent">

    <!-- Your content goes here -->

</com.example.myapp.NonScrollableScrollView>
```

Keep in mind that by doing this, you'll prevent the `ScrollView` from scrolling entirely, so you should consider other ways to navigate or interact with the content if necessary.

