[ASSISTANT] To check the number of touches in an Android application, you can override the `onTouchEvent` method in your Activity or View. Here's an example of how you can do it:

```java
@Override
public boolean onTouchEvent(MotionEvent event) {
    int action = event.getActionMasked();

    int pointerCount = event.getPointerCount(); // Get the number of active pointers

    switch (action) {
        case MotionEvent.ACTION_DOWN:
            // Single touch down
            break;
        case MotionEvent.ACTION_POINTER_DOWN:
            // Additional touch down (multi-touch)
            break;
        case MotionEvent.ACTION_MOVE:
            // Movement event
            break;
        case MotionEvent.ACTION_POINTER_UP:
            // Additional touch up (multi-touch)
            break;
        case MotionEvent.ACTION_UP:
            // Single touch up
            break;
    }

    // Process the event as needed

    return true; // Return true to indicate that you've consumed the event
}
```

In this example, `event.getPointerCount()` will give you the number of active touches on the screen. The MotionEvent actions are used to distinguish between different touch events, like down, move, up, and additional pointers going down or up.

Remember to return `true` at the end of `onTouchEvent` to indicate that you've consumed the event. If you return `false`, the system will continue to propagate the event to other views.

Keep in mind that if you're working with a `View` inside an `Activity`, you'll need to override `onTouchEvent` in that `View` class. If you're working directly in an `Activity`, you can override it there.

