[ASSISTANT] In Android, the `ACTION_POINTER_DOWN` event is triggered when a non-primary pointer (i.e., not the first finger touching the screen) goes down. This typically happens in a multi-touch scenario when additional fingers touch the screen.

Here is an example of how you can handle the `ACTION_POINTER_DOWN` event in Kotlin:

```kotlin
override fun onTouchEvent(event: MotionEvent): Boolean {
    val action = event.actionMasked
    val pointerCount = event.pointerCount // Get the number of active pointers

    when (action) {
        MotionEvent.ACTION_DOWN -> {
            // Single touch down
        }
        MotionEvent.ACTION_POINTER_DOWN -> {
            val pointerIndex = event.actionIndex // Get the index of the pointer
            val pointerId = event.getPointerId(pointerIndex) // Get the pointer ID

            // Additional touch down (multi-touch)
